<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="67" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,152,1018]" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,340,711,737]" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">Comments.</emphasis>
This species is distinguished by its pronotal shape: convex anteriorly and highly elevated above humeral angles. In this respect, it resembles only 
<taxonomicName authority="Evangelista &amp; Sakakibara, 2007" authorityName="Evangelista &amp; Sakakibara" authorityYear="2007" box="[814,1431,752,778]" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Amastris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gibberula">
<emphasis box="[814,1041,752,777]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">Amastris gibberula</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Evangelista" box="[1049,1431,752,778]" pageId="4" pageNumber="68" refString="Evangelista, O. &amp; Sakakibara, A. M. (2007) New species of the treehopper tribe Amastrini (Hemiptera, Membracidae, Smiliinae). Revista Brasileira de Entomologia, 51 (1), 38 - 41." type="journal article" year="2007">
Evangelista &amp; Sakakibara, 
<number box="[1370,1431,752,778]" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" value="2007.0">2007</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, among all 
<taxonomicName box="[278,382,792,817]" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Amastris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[278,382,792,817]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">Amastris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species. The simple, U-shaped aedeagus, with small denticles on the anterior surface, is identical to that of the 
<emphasis box="[415,553,832,857]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">funkhouseri</emphasis>
-group, established by 
<bibRefCitation author="Broomfield" box="[820,1040,832,858]" pageId="4" pageNumber="68" refString="Broomfield, P. S. (1976) A revision of the genus Amastris (Homoptera, Membracidae). Bulletin of the British Museum, 33 (4), 347 - 460." type="journal article" year="1976">
Broomfield (
<number box="[971,1032,832,858]" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" value="1976.0">1976</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
for some species of 
<taxonomicName box="[1283,1387,832,857]" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Amastris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1283,1387,832,857]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">Amastris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,152,1018]" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">
The male 
<typeStatus box="[315,416,872,898]" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">paratype</typeStatus>
has the head entirely yellow, sparsely spotted with dark brown. The female 
<typeStatus box="[1308,1409,872,898]" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">paratype</typeStatus>
is badly damaged: the right half of the head, the left eye and the three left legs are missing, and only a part of the right side legs remain, with coxa, trocanter and tibia. It is glued to a card; due to its position, some measurements were estimated.
</paragraph>
